<%# Layout-level notifications modal.

    The navbar `[notifications]` link opens this modal instead of doing a
    full-page navigation to /notifications. The dialog hosts a Turbo
    Frame (`notifications_modal_frame`); the Stimulus
    `notifications-modal` controller (mounted on `<body>`) sets the
    frame's `src` to `/notifications?modal=yes` on open. The server-
    side index template wraps its body in a matching `turbo-frame` when
    `params[:modal] == "yes"`, so Turbo finds the frame and swaps in the
    list, filter chip, dynamic mark-button, and the nested detail-modal
    `<dialog>` Phase 16 already wired up.

    Direct navigation to `/notifications` still works — when `modal=yes`
    is absent the controller renders the standard full-page index with
    layout, so JS-off / direct-link users get the same content.

    Closing semantics mirror the project's other layout-level modals
    (search, IGDB search):
      - Escape — native <dialog>.
      - Click outside — `clickOutside` action.
      - `[close]` button — `close` action on the controller.
    No JS `confirm()` / `alert()` / `prompt()` (CLAUDE.md hard rule). %>
<dialog id="notifications-modal"
        class="pane-dialog notifications-modal"
        data-action="click->notifications-modal#clickOutside keydown->notifications-modal#keydown">
  <div style="padding: 12px 16px; min-width: 480px; max-width: 900px; max-height: 80vh; overflow-y: auto;">
    <%= turbo_frame_tag "notifications_modal_frame",
                        src: nil,
                        loading: "lazy",
                        data: { notifications_modal_target: "frame" } %>
    <div class="modal-footer">
      <button type="button" class="bracketed" data-action="notifications-modal#close">[<span class="bl">close</span>]</button>
    </div>
  </div>
</dialog>
